---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<Layout title="Install · kumiki">
  <section class="install">
    <h1>Getting Started</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      kumiki is a Python timber-framing library used through the <strong>kigumi</strong> VS Code
      extension. Follow the steps below to go from zero to your first 3D timber frame.
    </p>

    <!-- ─── SETUP STEPS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

    <div class="steps">

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">1</span>
          <h2>Install VS Code</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Download and install <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Visual Studio Code</a> for your platform. Any recent version works.
            </p>
          </div>
          {/* image slot — add <img> here when ready */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">2</span>
          <h2>Install the kigumi VS Code extension</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Install the <a href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=minimaple.kigumi" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">kigumi extension from the VS Code Marketplace</a>.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Using <strong>Cursor</strong>? kigumi is also <a href="https://open-vsx.org/extension/minimaple/kigumi" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">available on OpenVSX</a>.</li>
              <li>Prefer a manual install? Grab the <code>.vsix</code> file from the <a href="https://github.com/minimapletinytools/kumiki/releases" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">releases page</a>.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">3</span>
          <h2>Install Python or uv</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Skip this step if you already have Python or <code>uv</code> installed. Otherwise, install one of:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/getting-started/installation/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">uv</a> — fast Python environment manager (recommended)</li>
              <li><a href="https://www.python.org/downloads/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Python</a> — standard Python installer</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="step-group-break">
      <span class="step-group-label">Open a project</span>
    </div>

    <div class="steps">

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">4</span>
          <h2>Create and open a workspace folder</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Create a new folder anywhere on your machine, then in VS Code choose
              <strong>File › Open Folder</strong> and open it. This folder becomes your kigumi project workspace.
            </p>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">5</span>
          <h2>Open the kigumi sidebar</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>Find the kigumi sidebar — it's the kumiki icon in the VS Code activity bar. A few ways to get there:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Click the kigumi icon in the vertical column on the left side of VS Code.</li>
              <li>It may be tucked inside a dropdown at the top of the left panel.</li>
              <li>Open the command palette (<kbd>Cmd/Ctrl + Shift + P</kbd>) and choose <strong>View: Show kigumi</strong>.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">6</span>
          <h2>Initialize your project</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              In the kigumi sidebar, click the <strong>Initialize Project</strong> button and wait a few seconds.
              This installs kumiki and creates the necessary project files in your workspace.
            </p>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="step-group-break">
      <span class="step-group-label">Start designing</span>
    </div>

    <div class="steps">

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">7</span>
          <h2>Explore frames and patterns</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Once initialized, the kigumi sidebar shows two kinds of items:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Frames</strong> — your own design files (<code>.py</code> scripts).</li>
              <li><strong>Patterns</strong> — bundled joint examples you can browse, open, and duplicate into your workspace.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">8</span>
          <h2>Open your first frame</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Click <strong>my_cute_frame</strong> in the sidebar to open it in the kigumi viewer.
              Edit <code>my_cute_frame.py</code> and click the <strong>refresh</strong> button in the viewer to see your changes live.
            </p>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-header">
          <span class="step-num">9</span>
          <h2>Add new frames</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-content">
            <p>
              Any new <code>.py</code> frame file you create will appear in the <strong>Frames</strong> section of the
              kigumi sidebar. If it doesn't show up immediately, click the sidebar's <strong>refresh</strong> button.
            </p>
          </div>
          {/* image slot */}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- ─── AI USAGE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

    <div class="ai-section">
      <h2>Using AI to design frames</h2>
      <p>
        kumiki frames are written in Python, which means AI coding agents can write them for you.
        VS Code ships with <a href="https://github.com/features/copilot/ai-code-editor" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">GitHub Copilot</a> — a great starting point.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The <strong>free Copilot tier</strong> can handle simple frames but has rate limits.</li>
        <li>The <strong>$10/mo plan</strong> gives you enough headroom for most design work.</li>
        <li>Any other coding agent works too — Cursor, Claude, ChatGPT, etc.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="prompt-example">
        <p class="prompt-label">Try asking your agent something like:</p>
        <blockquote>
          "Make me a cute saw horse. It has 2 horizontal feet on a 1'×2' footprint, with two
          vertical legs on top of the feet, and a horizontal beam resting on top of the 2 legs.
          There should also be a stretcher connecting the 2 legs in the middle. Join everything
          with mortise and tenon joinery with square pegs please!"
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── CTA ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="https://github.com/minimapletinytools/kumiki" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
        View on GitHub
      </a>
      <a class="btn btn-secondary" href={`${base}/`}>
        Back to home
      </a>
    </div>

  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .install {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.2rem 0 2rem;
  }
  .install h1 {
    font-size: 2.2rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .lead {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    margin: 0 0 2.4rem;
    max-width: 600px;
  }

  /* ── Step group breaks ── */
  .step-group-break {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    margin: 2rem 0 1.4rem 0;
  }
  .step-group-break::before,
  .step-group-break::after {
    content: '';
    flex: 1;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--border);
  }
  .step-group-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.09em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  /* ── Steps ── */
  .steps {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--border);
    margin-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .step {
    position: relative;
    padding: 0 0 2.2rem 2.2rem;
  }
  .step:last-child { padding-bottom: 0; }

  .step-num {
    position: absolute;
    left: -1.1rem;
    top: 0.05rem;
    width: 2.2rem;
    height: 2.2rem;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--surface);
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: inline-grid;
    place-items: center;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .step-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .step-header h2 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    margin: 0.2rem 0 0;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .step-body {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  /* When an image is added, uncomment to go side-by-side:
  @media (min-width: 600px) {
    .step-body { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }
  */

  .step-content p,
  .step-content ul {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .step-content ul {
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
  }
  .step-content li { margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }

  /* image placeholder — remove once real images are added */
  .step-body img {
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 0.6rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    display: block;
  }

  /* ── AI section ── */
  .ai-section {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.4rem;
  }
  .ai-section h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
  }
  .ai-section p,
  .ai-section ul {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
  }
  .ai-section ul { padding-left: 1.2rem; }
  .ai-section li { margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }

  .prompt-example {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-soft);
    border-radius: 0.6rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
    margin-top: 1rem;
  }
  .prompt-label {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem !important;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }
  .prompt-example blockquote {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* ── Shared ── */
  code {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.3rem;
    padding: 0.05rem 0.35rem;
    font-size: 0.92em;
  }
  kbd {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.3rem;
    padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;
    font-size: 0.88em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;
  }
  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
